{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"940"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/940"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.07,0.02,0.01,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54767"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/940"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"339"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54767"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of pain over both pre-auricular regions. He has been at home for the past two weeks recovering from a flare-up of his known Crohn\u0027s disease, which had required a two-week hospital admission and commencement of corticosteroids. He also has a medical history of depression and is currently attempting to quit cigarette smoking. His regular medications include azathioprine, sertraline for depression, and nicotine replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There is warmth and tenderness on palpation of the pre-auricular regions. Pus is expressed from the parotid ducts. There is no evidence of a dental abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous antibiotics","Conservative measures only","Oral hydration","Lidocaine mouth gel","Surgical washout"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of bacterial parotitis, including bilateral pre-auricular pain, fever, and expression of pus from the parotid ducts. His recent hospitalisation and immunosuppression due to Crohn\u0027s disease and corticosteroid treatment are significant risk factors for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are the mainstay of treatment for bacterial parotitis. This approach is crucial to prevent complications such as localised cellulitis and septicaemia. The recommended empirical antibiotic regimen is flucloxacillin, as \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E is the most common causative organism, although the infection is often polymicrobial. However in immuncompromised people or those at higher risk of MRSA (as in this patient) broader-spectrum antibiotics should be used. If not clinically improving, pus swabs can be taken for culture to guide management\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative measures\u003C/strong\u003E such as local heat application and gentle massage can be helpful adjuncts to antibiotic therapy, but they are insufficient as standalone treatment for bacterial parotitis. These measures may help with symptom relief and promote drainage but do not address the underlying infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral hydration\u003C/strong\u003E is important in the management of parotitis as it helps stimulate saliva production and may aid in flushing out the infected material. However, it is not the primary treatment and should be used in conjunction with antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELidocaine mouth gel\u003C/strong\u003E is a local anaesthetic that may provide temporary pain relief but does not treat the underlying infection. It is not an appropriate primary management strategy for bacterial parotitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical washout\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically the first-line treatment for parotitis. It is only considered if there is no response to a full course of IV antibiotics. In most cases, antibiotic therapy is sufficient. If abscesses are present, needle aspiration under ultrasound guidance may be performed before considering more invasive surgical intervention. This allows for both diagnostic (culture of aspirate) and therapeutic benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to intravenous antibiotics, management should include supportive care, pain control, and close monitoring. Further investigations such as ultrasound or CT scan may be warranted to assess for abscess formation. Culture and sensitivity testing of the expressed pus can guide targeted antibiotic therapy if the patient does not respond to empirical treatment. If abscesses are identified, they may be aspirated under ultrasound guidance, but this would typically occur after initial antibiotic therapy has been initiated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bacterial parotitis presents with an inflamed parotid gland, expression of pus, and infective symptoms.","Intravenous antibiotics are the mainstay treatment for bacterial parotitis","Risk factors for bacterial parotitis include immunosuppression and recent hospitalisation."],"references":["Salivary gland infections. Oral and Dental Therapeutic guidelines. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited [online]. 2022; cited 2022 Jul 10. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au/","Srivanitchapoom C, Yata K. Clinical characteristics that predict parotid abscess: An observational cohort study. Annals of Medicine and Surgery. 2021 Apr 1;64:102230. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33777393/","Chow A. Suppurative parotitis in adults. UpToDate. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/suppurative-parotitis-in-adults"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"940"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T21:19:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T21:20:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"940"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54767"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headin